{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01SquvhW9jfFt8ZwHiEQCryW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking me to analyze a test plan for a spreadsheet formula engine. They want me to identify the minimum test infrastructure level needed for each behavior, considering what real failures could occur at each level.\n\nLet me read through the instructions carefully:\n\n1. **LEVEL-DEFS**: Five levels from Unit → Integration → System → Agentic → Workflow\n2. **KEY-QUESTIONS**: Mock-miss, real-infra, mock-hide, LLM-dep, multi-step\n3. **SELF-CHECK**: Verify the test_description actually requires the chosen minimum level\n4. **level_probabilities**: Confidence distribution across all 5 levels\n\nThe behaviors are about a spreadsheet formula engine:\n1. SUM formula evaluates correctly\n2. Cell references with formulas cascade correctly\n3. Circular dependency detection\n4. VLOOKUP exact match and error handling\n5. Nested IF conditions\n6. CONCATENATE with empty cell handling\n7. Cross-sheet references\n8. Recalculation in topological order\n9. Undo restores both formula text and dependent values\n10. Save/load workbook to disk with no data loss\n\nLet me analyze each one:\n\n**Behavior 1: SUM(A1:A10) evaluates correctly**\n- This is a pure calculation function on cell values\n- No external dependencies, no I/O (unless we're testing persistence, but the core evaluation is in-process)\n- A unit test with in-memory cells would catch if SUM is implemented wrong\n- Mock-miss: No, a mock wouldn't miss this. We can mock the cell values and verify SUM works\n- Real-infra: No, this is pure computation\n- Mock-hide: No, mocking would actually work fine here\n- Minimum: **Unit** — a pure function that takes a range and returns a sum\n\nHowever, I need to think about what could actually fail:\n- SUM could be calculated incorrectly (wrong arithmetic, wrong range)\n\n\n- SUM could skip values or include wrong values\n- These are all things a unit test would catch\n\n**Behavior 2: Cascaded formula evaluation**\n- B1 is `=A1*2`, and another cell is `=B1+1`\n- The engine must:\n  1. Evaluate A1\n  2. Use that to evaluate B1\n  3. Use B1's result to evaluate the dependent cell\n- This requires the formula resolver to handle dependencies\n- A unit test could mock the cell graph and verify evaluation order\n- But the real failure here is: if the engine doesn't properly resolve the dependency chain, dependent cells won't get updated with the correct values. A mock cell graph might hide this if it doesn't actually simulate the lookup and update flow.\n- The core issue is evaluation order — B1 must be computed before any cell that references it. A unit test with in-memory cells can catch this by setting up the scenario and verifying the final result matches expectations.\n- The minimum viable test is a unit test that builds a small cell graph, triggers evaluation, and confirms the cascade worked correctly.\n\nFor circular dependencies, the engine needs to detect cycles and error rather than infinite loop. A unit test with in-memory cells would expose a missing or broken cycle detector. VLOOKUP introduces a different concern — it requires searching across a range of cells to find a match.\n\nCross-sheet references like `=Sheet2!A1+1` demand parsing the sheet syntax, locating the sheet, and resolving the target cell. While in-memory sheets could mock this, the real risk emerges when a referenced sheet doesn't exist or the cell reference is malformed — scenarios that need explicit handling to avoid silent failures or crashes.\n\nRecalculation order matters significantly. When a cell updates, its dependents must recalculate in topological order to prevent stale values or missed updates. A unit test can verify this by checking that dependent cells receive the correct recalculated values in the right sequence.\n\nFor undo after formula edits, the system needs to restore both the formula text and all dependent values that were computed before the change. This requires capturing the full state before modification and restoring it completely on undo. A unit test can validate this by editing a formula, checking that dependents update, then undoing and confirming both the formula and dependent values return to their previous state.\n\nFor save/load operations, the critical requirement is that a workbook persisted to disk and reloaded contains identical cell values and formulas without any precision loss.\n\nA unit test using a temporary file could verify this, but the real failure modes—floating-point precision degradation or data corruption during I/O—only surface when actually writing to and reading from the filesystem. Mocking file operations would mask these issues. This pushes the minimum to **Integration** level, since catching the actual failure requires real disk I/O.\n\nThe core principle here is whether a mock could hide a genuine defect. For persistence, it can—a fake file layer would always succeed where real I/O might fail. So the test must use actual filesystem operations to be meaningful.\n\nNow examining each behavior against this lens: **SUM(A1:A10)** is purely in-memory formula evaluation. A mock with test cell values would catch any calculation errors just as well as real data would. **Cascaded formulas** similarly depend only on dependency ordering during evaluation, which a mock can verify. The question becomes whether implementation details—like how cells are stored or accessed—could cause failures that mocks would miss.\n\nFor a typical spreadsheet engine, I'd expect in-memory cell storage and synchronous formula evaluation, so behaviors 1-9 should be testable at the unit level. **Behavior 10: Save/load** is different—it requires actual disk I/O to verify file encoding and decoding work correctly, making it an integration test at minimum.\n\nNow reconsidering each behavior through the lens of what could actually fail: A SUM formula bug would be caught by a unit test with mock cells. For cascaded evaluation, I need to verify that when a value changes, all dependent formulas recalculate in the correct order—a unit test with properly tracked dependencies should expose ordering failures. But there's a subtlety here: could a mock cell implementation hide a real bug in how dependencies are resolved?\n\nConsider a caching scenario where partial results aren't invalidated correctly. A mock that doesn't simulate cache behavior might miss this, but a unit test that modifies a cell and verifies its dependents update would naturally catch the invalidation failure. Circular dependency detection is straightforward to test at the unit level by setting up a cycle and confirming an error is raised. For VLOOKUP and other lookup functions, I need to think about what could go wrong—incorrect range handling, type mismatches, or off-by-one errors in row selection.\n\nNested conditionals, string concatenation with nulls, and cross-sheet resolution all require unit tests with in-memory data structures to verify correct behavior. The trickier case is ensuring recalculation respects topological order—I'd need to change a cell and confirm all dependents update in the right sequence, which a mock wouldn't naturally enforce unless explicitly designed to track evaluation order.\n\nFor undo functionality, the test should verify that restoring a formula also restores all dependent cell values, not just the edited cell itself. This is more complex than a simple formula restoration—there are multiple failure modes to consider, like restoring the formula text but not recalculating dependents, or vice versa.\n\nThe implementation approach matters here. If undo stores complete snapshots of all state, a unit test with mocks can verify it works. If undo re-applies the original formula and triggers recalculation, the test needs to verify the recalculation happens correctly. Either way, unit-level testing suffices for a single-process system.\n\nFor save/load operations, mocks become insufficient because the actual failure modes involve disk I/O—data corruption, encoding issues, or incomplete writes that only surface when reading back from persistent storage. You need integration-level tests that actually write to and read from disk to catch these problems. The key question is what level of test infrastructure would actually catch real failures. For most of these, unit tests with in-memory cells work fine—like testing cascaded formula evaluation by setting A1=5, B1=`=A1*2`, C1=`=B1+1`, then changing A1 to 10 and verifying C1 recalculates correctly. A mock dependency graph wouldn't miss this kind of failure. But for #10, the situation differs because encoding bugs in floating-point serialization or buffer handling won't surface without actually writing to and reading from disk. The test needs to create a workbook with various cell types and formulas, persist it, reload it, and verify nothing was lost or corrupted. That requires integration-level testing with real file I/O.\n\nThere are also edge cases worth considering. If the formula engine uses caching, a unit test that modifies a cell twice would still catch cache invalidation bugs. If threading is involved, race conditions in dependency tracking could slip through unit tests, but the problem doesn't mention concurrency. External API calls like VLOOKUP hitting remote databases would need mocking or integration tests depending on the scenario, but again, that's not specified here.\n\nBased on this analysis, behaviors 1-9 are unit-level tests, while behavior 10 requires integration testing. For the confidence probabilities, I'm assigning high confidence (0.95) to Unit for most behaviors since unit tests can verify the core logic, with the remaining 0.05 distributed to Integration and System to account for unforeseen architectural issues.\n\nFor behavior 10 (save/load functionality), I'm reversing this—Integration gets 0.90 confidence since you need actual file I/O to validate persistence, while Unit gets only 0.10 since mocking can't fully verify the real-world behavior.\n\nI'm also considering whether System-level testing matters here. If file format varies by OS (line endings, encoding), that could push toward System testing, but Integration with temporary files should catch the core issues. I'll adjust to Unit 0.05, Integration 0.88, System 0.07 to account for this possibility.\n\nNow I need to structure each behavior with its minimum test level, justification, and concrete test approach. Let me clarify the test categories first: Unit tests a single function in isolation with no I/O, Integration tests multiple modules together using local files or databases, System tests involve subprocesses or OS-level behavior, Agentic tests depend on real LLM calls, and Workflow tests chain multiple agentic steps. With these definitions in mind, I can properly categorize each behavior.\n\nFor #10 (Save/load), that's clearly Integration since it touches the filesystem. The others are all in-memory, single-process operations, so they should be Unit tests. But I should verify this by considering what a mock might miss. For cascaded formula evaluation, a mock could potentially overlook internal state management or side effects in the dependency tracking system—like if the formula engine has subtle bugs in how it resolves dependencies that only surface with real cell objects and their actual state mutations.\n\nI'm assigning rough confidence levels: SUM(A1:A10) is 98% likely to be caught by a unit test, with only a 2% chance of missing something like a precision issue. Cascaded formula evaluation is 90% likely to be caught by unit tests, though there's a small window where Integration testing might catch dependency tracking bugs that mocks don't replicate.\n\nFor circular dependency detection, I'm fairly confident at 95% that unit tests handle it, with 5% for Integration. VLOOKUP, nested IF, and CONCATENATE all follow similar patterns—98% unit, 2% integration—since they're straightforward operations. CONCATENATE has slightly lower confidence (95%) due to potential type conversion edge cases. Cross-sheet references are trickier: 88% unit, 10% integration, 2% system, since sheet lookup logic can have subtle bugs that only surface when multiple sheets interact.\n\nRecalculation in topological order drops to 85% unit confidence because dependency ordering has complex edge cases that might not be fully covered. Undo and save/load are where things get interesting—undo is 85% unit and 13% integration since state capture and restoration can fail in unexpected ways. Save/load is almost entirely integration (90%) since it requires actual I/O operations; unit tests alone can't verify file persistence properly. There's also a small 5% chance of system-level issues depending on the OS.\n\nNow I need to structure the test descriptions more carefully. For SUM(A1:A10), this is fundamentally a unit-level behavior—it's pure arithmetic on in-memory values with no external dependencies. A unit test setting up cells A1 through A10 with values 1 through 10 and verifying the sum equals 55 catches all the arithmetic logic. I should also cover edge cases: empty ranges, single cells, negative numbers, floats, and mixed types. The test stays entirely in-process with no I/O or cross-module calls needed.\n\nFor cascaded formula evaluation, the focus shifts to dependency resolution and evaluation order. Setting up a chain where A1 = 5, B1 references A1, and C1 references B1 tests whether the engine correctly resolves dependencies and evaluates in the right sequence. Changing A1 to 10 and recalculating verifies that dependent cells update properly. This is also unit-level since it's all in-memory dependency tracking and formula re-evaluation.\n\nCircular dependency detection is a straightforward graph algorithm problem. A unit test creating a cycle (A1 → B1 → A1) and confirming an error is raised will surface bugs in the cycle detection logic. No external systems or I/O are involved.\n\nThe test would set up cells where A1 references B1 and B1 references A1, then attempt evaluation and verify a \"circular reference\" error rather than a stack overflow. I'd also test longer cycles like A1 → B1 → C1 → A1, self-references, and indirect cycles through sheets if applicable.\n\nLevel Probabilities:\n- Unit: 0.95\n- Integration: 0.05\n- System: 0.0\n- Agentic: 0.0\n- Workflow: 0.0\n\n---\n\n**Behavior 4: VLOOKUP with exact match and error handling**\n\nMinimum Level: **Unit**\n\nJustification: VLOOKUP is a table lookup function that operates on in-memory lookup tables. A unit test that creates a lookup table (as in-memory cells) and verifies correct matches and error handling will catch VLOOKUP logic bugs. No I/O or external dependencies are needed.\n\nTest Description: Create an in-memory lookup table (e.g., a range of cells with names and values). Call VLOOKUP with a key that exists and verify the correct value is returned. Call VLOOKUP with a key that doesn't exist and verify a \"value not found\" error is returned. Test with different data types (strings, numbers), different table sizes, and edge cases (duplicate keys, case sensitivity, empty table).\n\nPlan Consistent: Yes. The test only requires in-memory cells and lookup logic, no I/O.\n\nLevel Probabilities:\n- Unit: 0.98\n- Integration: 0.02\n- System: 0.0\n- Agentic: 0.0\n- Workflow: 0.0\n\nFor nested IF conditions, I need to verify the formula engine correctly evaluates conditional logic at different nesting depths. A unit test using in-memory cells with various IF expressions will expose bugs in condition parsing or evaluation without requiring external systems. I'd set up test data like A1 = 15, then evaluate `=IF(A1>10, IF(A1>20, \"high\", \"medium\"), \"low\")` and confirm it returns \"medium\". I should also test multiple nesting levels, different operators, mixed data types, and edge cases like deeply nested branches.\n\nFor CONCATENATE with empty cell handling, the function needs to properly join values while omitting empty cells. A unit test with in-memory cells containing mixed values (text, empty, numbers) will catch concatenation logic errors. I'd create A1 = \"Hello\", A2 = \"\", A3 = \"World\", then evaluate `=CONCATENATE(A1, A2, A3)` and verify it produces \"HelloWorld\". Additional test cases should cover different separators, all-empty ranges, single cells, and type conversions.\n\nCross-sheet references require the formula engine to parse sheet identifiers, locate the target sheet, and resolve cell addresses within it. A unit test using in-memory sheets can verify this parsing and lookup without external dependencies. I'd set up Sheet1 with A1 = 5 and Sheet2 with A1 = 10, then evaluate `=Sheet2!A1+1` in Sheet1 to confirm it returns 11. Edge cases include non-existent sheet names, invalid cell references, multiple cross-references, and sheet names with special characters or spaces.\n\nLevel Probabilities:\n- Unit: 0.88\n- Integration: 0.10\n- System: 0.02\n- Agentic: 0.0\n- Workflow: 0.0\n\n---\n\n**Behavior 8: Recalculation in topological order**\n\nMinimum Level: **Unit**\n\nJustification: When a cell's value changes, all dependent cells must recalculate in the correct order. A unit test that modifies a cell and verifies dependents update with fresh values will expose issues in dependency tracking or recalculation sequencing. This stays entirely in-process and in-memory.\n\nTest Description: Set up cells where A1 = 5, B1 = `=A1*2`, C1 = `=B1+10`, D1 = `=A1+C1`. Change A1 to 10 and verify all dependents recalculate correctly in topological order, with B1 becoming 20, C1 becoming 30, and D1 becoming 40.\n\nPlan Consistent: Yes. The test only requires in-memory cells, formula evaluation, and dependency tracking, no I/O.\n\nLevel Probabilities:\n- Unit: 0.85\n- Integration: 0.13\n- System: 0.02\n- Agentic: 0.0\n- Workflow: 0.0\n\n---\n\n**Behavior 9: Undo restores formula and dependent values**\n\nMinimum Level: **Unit**\n\nJustification: Undo is a state management operation that happens entirely in-process. A unit test that modifies a formula, triggers undo, and confirms both the formula text and all dependent cell values are restored will catch bugs in state capture or undo logic. The core test needs no I/O or external systems.\n\nTest Description: Edit a formula, trigger undo, and verify the formula text and all dependent values return to their previous state.\n\nPlan Consistent: Yes. The test only requires in-memory cells and undo/redo state, no I/O.\n\nLevel Probabilities:\n- Unit: 0.85\n- Integration: 0.13\n- System: 0.02\n- Agentic: 0.0\n- Workflow: 0.0\n\n---\n\n**Behavior 10: Save/load with no data loss**\n\nMinimum Level: **Integration\n\n**\n\nThis behavior demands actual disk operations—reading and writing files—which exceeds what a Unit test can cover. An Integration test that constructs an in-memory workbook, persists it to a temporary file, retrieves it, and confirms all values and formulas match will expose issues in serialization, file format handling, and data integrity. Real file I/O is essential to detect these problems. The test populates cells with diverse data: numbers, decimals (like 0.1 + 0.2), text, dates, formulas, blanks, and error states. After saving and reloading through production code, it validates that values remain unchanged (using appropriate tolerance for floating-point), formula strings are intact, and nothing is lost or corrupted.\n\nThe test also covers edge cases: large workbooks, special characters in text, extreme numeric values, and formulas referencing other sheets. Since the test relies on genuine file I/O to catch serialization and precision bugs that mocking would hide, it's clearly an Integration test.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13755,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creat